Note:
==============================================================================
FIELD25519 - Arithmetic in F_p with p = 2^255 - 19
==============================================================================

Foundation for Ed25519 (twisted Edwards) and X25519 (Montgomery). All field
operations are constant-time: no branches, no memory accesses, and no shifts
that depend on the limb values, only on the fixed limb layout.

Representation: 10 limbs of radix 2^25.5 (alternating 26-bit and 25-bit).
Limb i contains bits [floor(25.5*i), floor(25.5*(i+1))) of the field value.
  limb 0: 26 bits  (bits   0..25)
  limb 1: 25 bits  (bits  26..50)
  limb 2: 26 bits  (bits  51..76)
  limb 3: 25 bits  (bits  77..101)
  limb 4: 26 bits  (bits 102..127)
  limb 5: 25 bits  (bits 128..152)
  limb 6: 26 bits  (bits 153..178)
  limb 7: 25 bits  (bits 179..203)
  limb 8: 26 bits  (bits 204..229)
  limb 9: 25 bits  (bits 230..254)

Limbs are stored as 64-bit signed integers at consecutive 8-byte offsets.
A field element occupies FIELD25519_BYTES = 80 bytes of arena memory.

The 26/25 layout (TweetNaCl ref10) lets a limb-limb multiplication produce a
~52-bit product, and the sum of 10 such products fits in ~58 bits, which is
well within 64-bit signed range with room for carry propagation. The
reduction 2^255 = 19 (mod p) is folded inline: any bit above position 254 is
multiplied by 19 and reabsorbed into the low limbs.

Reference:
- D.J. Bernstein, "Curve25519: new Diffie-Hellman speed records", PKC 2006.
- RFC 7748 section 5 (X25519).
- RFC 8032 section 5.1 (Ed25519).
- ref10 reference implementation in TweetNaCl / SUPERCOP.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena

Constant FIELD25519_BYTES as Integer is 80
Constant FIELD25519_MASK26 as Integer is 67108863
Constant FIELD25519_MASK25 as Integer is 33554431
Constant FIELD25519_TWO_TO_26 as Integer is 67108864
Constant FIELD25519_TWO_TO_25 as Integer is 33554432

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1: Limb load/store + element allocation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe25519_alloc" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates an 80-byte buffer in the arena to hold a 10-limb field
    element. Initial value is 0 (all limbs zero from arena_allocate's
    contract, but we explicitly zero in case the arena reused memory).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocates 80 bytes, writes zero to each of the ten 8-byte limb cells.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) ten-store loop. Same cost as a memset of a tenth of a cache line.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The zeroing leaves no residual data in the buffer. The buffer itself
    is arena-backed and lives until arena_reset / arena_destroy.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let buffer be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, FIELD25519_BYTES)
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 10:
        Memory.memory_set_qword(buffer, i multiplied by 8, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return buffer
End Process

Process called "fe25519_get_limb" takes fe as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reads the index-th 26-or-25-bit limb of a field element. Index must be
    in [0, 9]. Returns 0 for out-of-range to keep callers branchless on
    invalid indices.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    The read is at a fixed offset determined by the index argument. When
    the index is a compile-time constant (as it always is in the inlined
    arithmetic kernels below), this is constant-time. When the index is a
    runtime value, the memory access pattern depends only on the index,
    not on the field element value.
    @End Security_Scope

    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If index is greater than 9:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, index multiplied by 8)
End Process

Process called "fe25519_set_limb" takes fe as Integer, index as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes a single limb. Range-checks the index for safety.
    @End Reasoning
    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If index is greater than 9:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, index multiplied by 8, value)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe25519_copy" takes dest as Integer, src as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Limb-wise copy of a field element. Used by point addition kernels to
    save intermediate state. Constant-time: ten unconditional 64-bit reads
    and writes.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    The copy never branches on limb contents.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 10:
        Let li be Memory.memory_get_int64(src, i multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, i multiplied by 8, li)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe25519_set_zero" takes fe as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Sets the field element to 0. Constant-time: ten unconditional writes.
    @End Reasoning
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 10:
        Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, i multiplied by 8, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe25519_set_one" takes fe as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Sets the field element to 1 (limb0 = 1, all others zero).
    @End Reasoning
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 0, 1)
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than 10:
        Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, i multiplied by 8, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2: Add, Sub, Neg (linear ops, no reduction needed inline)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe25519_add" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Component-wise addition: dest[i] = a[i] + b[i] for i in [0, 9]. With
    26/25-bit limbs and bounded inputs, the sum fits in at most 27 bits per
    limb, well within signed 64-bit range. No reduction is performed here;
    callers that need normalized output must call fe25519_reduce.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Ten unconditional add/store operations.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Bounded inputs (|a_i|, |b_i| < 2^54) keep the result well clear of the
    63-bit signed limit even across many chained additions.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. No data-dependent branches or memory accesses.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 10:
        Let ai be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, i multiplied by 8)
        Let bi be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, i multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, i multiplied by 8, ai plus bi)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe25519_sub" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Component-wise subtraction: dest[i] = a[i] - b[i]. Sign is preserved in
    each limb (signed 64-bit). Reduction is deferred to fe25519_reduce.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: ten unconditional sub/store operations.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 10:
        Let ai be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, i multiplied by 8)
        Let bi be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, i multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, i multiplied by 8, ai minus bi)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe25519_neg" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Negation: dest[i] = -a[i]. Result has the same magnitude bound as a.
    @End Reasoning
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 10:
        Let ai be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, i multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, i multiplied by 8, 0 minus ai)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3: Carry propagation + canonical reduction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe25519_carry" takes h as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Propagates carries through the ten limbs to bring each into its target
    range (26 or 25 bits, signed). The overflow from limb 9 (top, 25-bit)
    wraps to limb 0 via the curve25519 reduction identity
    2^255 = 19 (mod p), so carry_9 * 19 is added back into limb 0.

    The carry uses arithmetic right shift (signed). When the language
    primitive is logical-shift-right of an unsigned 64-bit value, the
    same result is obtained by adding 2^25 (or 2^24) before shifting and
    subtracting 1 in the destination limb. We use signed shifts here
    because Runa Integer arithmetic is two's-complement signed, which is
    exactly what we need: a signed limb of value -1 right-shifted by 26
    is still -1, propagating sign correctly.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The pattern interleaves carries from even and odd limbs:
      c = (h[i] + 2^(s-1)) >> s
      h[i+1] += c
      h[i] -= c << s
    where s is 26 for even indices and 25 for odd. The interleave starts
    at limb 0, alternating up to limb 9, then a final wrap-around from
    limb 9 back into limb 0 with the factor of 19.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(n) over n=10 limbs. No multiplications except the constant 19 wrap.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: the carry pattern is fixed; only the limb values are
    data-dependent and they only affect arithmetic results, not control
    flow or memory addresses.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: First carry pass (single pass suffices when inputs are bounded
    Note: by the kernel guarantees of mul/sqr; chained sums may require
    Note: a second pass which the caller invokes).

    Note: limb 0 (26-bit) -> limb 1
    Let h0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 0)
    Let c0 be h0 plus 33554432
    Let c0_shr be c0 shifted right by 26
    Let h1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 8)
    Set h1 to h1 plus c0_shr
    Let c0_lo be c0_shr multiplied by 67108864
    Set h0 to h0 minus c0_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 0, h0)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 8, h1)

    Note: limb 1 (25-bit) -> limb 2
    Let c1 be h1 plus 16777216
    Let c1_shr be c1 shifted right by 25
    Let h2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 16)
    Set h2 to h2 plus c1_shr
    Let c1_lo be c1_shr multiplied by 33554432
    Set h1 to h1 minus c1_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 8, h1)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 16, h2)

    Note: limb 2 (26-bit) -> limb 3
    Let c2 be h2 plus 33554432
    Let c2_shr be c2 shifted right by 26
    Let h3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 24)
    Set h3 to h3 plus c2_shr
    Let c2_lo be c2_shr multiplied by 67108864
    Set h2 to h2 minus c2_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 16, h2)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 24, h3)

    Note: limb 3 (25-bit) -> limb 4
    Let c3 be h3 plus 16777216
    Let c3_shr be c3 shifted right by 25
    Let h4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 32)
    Set h4 to h4 plus c3_shr
    Let c3_lo be c3_shr multiplied by 33554432
    Set h3 to h3 minus c3_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 24, h3)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 32, h4)

    Note: limb 4 (26-bit) -> limb 5
    Let c4 be h4 plus 33554432
    Let c4_shr be c4 shifted right by 26
    Let h5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 40)
    Set h5 to h5 plus c4_shr
    Let c4_lo be c4_shr multiplied by 67108864
    Set h4 to h4 minus c4_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 32, h4)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 40, h5)

    Note: limb 5 (25-bit) -> limb 6
    Let c5 be h5 plus 16777216
    Let c5_shr be c5 shifted right by 25
    Let h6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 48)
    Set h6 to h6 plus c5_shr
    Let c5_lo be c5_shr multiplied by 33554432
    Set h5 to h5 minus c5_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 40, h5)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 48, h6)

    Note: limb 6 (26-bit) -> limb 7
    Let c6 be h6 plus 33554432
    Let c6_shr be c6 shifted right by 26
    Let h7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 56)
    Set h7 to h7 plus c6_shr
    Let c6_lo be c6_shr multiplied by 67108864
    Set h6 to h6 minus c6_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 48, h6)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 56, h7)

    Note: limb 7 (25-bit) -> limb 8
    Let c7 be h7 plus 16777216
    Let c7_shr be c7 shifted right by 25
    Let h8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 64)
    Set h8 to h8 plus c7_shr
    Let c7_lo be c7_shr multiplied by 33554432
    Set h7 to h7 minus c7_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 56, h7)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 64, h8)

    Note: limb 8 (26-bit) -> limb 9
    Let c8 be h8 plus 33554432
    Let c8_shr be c8 shifted right by 26
    Let h9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 72)
    Set h9 to h9 plus c8_shr
    Let c8_lo be c8_shr multiplied by 67108864
    Set h8 to h8 minus c8_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 64, h8)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 72, h9)

    Note: limb 9 (25-bit) -> wrap to limb 0 with factor 19
    Let c9 be h9 plus 16777216
    Let c9_shr be c9 shifted right by 25
    Let c9_lo be c9_shr multiplied by 33554432
    Set h9 to h9 minus c9_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 72, h9)

    Let wrap_in be c9_shr multiplied by 19
    Let h0b be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 0)
    Set h0b to h0b plus wrap_in
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 0, h0b)

    Note: Second carry from limb 0 only (rarely needs more after mul).
    Let h0c be h0b
    Let c0b be h0c plus 33554432
    Let c0b_shr be c0b shifted right by 26
    Let h1b be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 8)
    Set h1b to h1b plus c0b_shr
    Let c0b_lo be c0b_shr multiplied by 67108864
    Set h0c to h0c minus c0b_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 0, h0c)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 8, h1b)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4: Multiplication and squaring (the core kernel)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe25519_mul" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Schoolbook multiplication of two 10-limb radix-2^25.5 field elements,
    followed by inline reduction of indices 10..18 back into indices 0..9
    via the identity 2^255 = 19 (mod p). The result is stored in dest as
    a 10-limb field element with bounded magnitude that fe25519_carry can
    canonicalize.

    Layout: limb i has weight 2^(ceil(25.5*i)). Cross-product limb i*j
    contributes to output limb (i+j) with possibly a factor-of-2
    adjustment whenever the parity of i and j leads to a half-weight
    alignment mismatch (the 26/25 alternation requires the 2*a_i*b_j
    pattern from ref10).

    Reduction: output limb r=i+j with r >= 10 is wrapped into limb r-10
    with a factor of 19. The factor-of-2 adjustments described above are
    folded into the multipliers (1 or 2) and the wrap factor (19 or 38).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    We follow the ref10 fe_mul schedule (TweetNaCl): the multiplier values
    1, 2, 19, 38 are derived as:
      - 2: appears when both source limbs are odd (25-bit), so their
        product weight is 2^(25.5*(i+j)) - we cannot represent half-weights
        in integer limbs, so we double the coefficient and the destination
        limb's weight is taken as ceil(25.5*(i+j)) = 25.5*(i+j) + 0.5.
      - 19: wrap factor for r >= 10 when neither doubling nor halving
        applies.
      - 38: combination of 2 (parity) and 19 (wrap).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    100 multiplications + ~100 additions + 10 carries. On x86-64 each
    multiplication is a single IMUL; on AArch64 a single MADD. The kernel
    is purely arithmetic with no branches, ideal for superscalar issue.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. The schedule of multiplications and additions is
    fixed at compile time; only the limb values are data-dependent. No
    table lookups, no conditional branches, no memory accesses that
    depend on secret data.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 0)
    Let a1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 8)
    Let a2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 16)
    Let a3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 24)
    Let a4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 32)
    Let a5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 40)
    Let a6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 48)
    Let a7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 56)
    Let a8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 64)
    Let a9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 72)

    Let b0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 0)
    Let b1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 8)
    Let b2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 16)
    Let b3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 24)
    Let b4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 32)
    Let b5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 40)
    Let b6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 48)
    Let b7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 56)
    Let b8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 64)
    Let b9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 72)

    Note: Precompute 19*b_i and 2*a_i for the odd-indexed (25-bit) a limbs.
    Let b1_19 be b1 multiplied by 19
    Let b2_19 be b2 multiplied by 19
    Let b3_19 be b3 multiplied by 19
    Let b4_19 be b4 multiplied by 19
    Let b5_19 be b5 multiplied by 19
    Let b6_19 be b6 multiplied by 19
    Let b7_19 be b7 multiplied by 19
    Let b8_19 be b8 multiplied by 19
    Let b9_19 be b9 multiplied by 19

    Let a1_2 be a1 multiplied by 2
    Let a3_2 be a3 multiplied by 2
    Let a5_2 be a5 multiplied by 2
    Let a7_2 be a7 multiplied by 2
    Let a9_2 be a9 multiplied by 2

    Note: r0 = a0*b0 + 38*(a1*b9 + a3*b7 + a5*b5 + a7*b3 + a9*b1)
    Note:        + 19*(a2*b8 + a4*b6 + a6*b4 + a8*b2)
    Let r0 be a0 multiplied by b0
    Set r0 to r0 plus a1_2 multiplied by b9_19
    Set r0 to r0 plus a2 multiplied by b8_19
    Set r0 to r0 plus a3_2 multiplied by b7_19
    Set r0 to r0 plus a4 multiplied by b6_19
    Set r0 to r0 plus a5_2 multiplied by b5_19
    Set r0 to r0 plus a6 multiplied by b4_19
    Set r0 to r0 plus a7_2 multiplied by b3_19
    Set r0 to r0 plus a8 multiplied by b2_19
    Set r0 to r0 plus a9_2 multiplied by b1_19

    Note: r1 = a0*b1 + a1*b0 + 19*(a2*b9 + a3*b8 + a4*b7 + a5*b6 + a6*b5 + a7*b4 + a8*b3 + a9*b2)
    Let r1 be a0 multiplied by b1
    Set r1 to r1 plus a1 multiplied by b0
    Set r1 to r1 plus a2 multiplied by b9_19
    Set r1 to r1 plus a3 multiplied by b8_19
    Set r1 to r1 plus a4 multiplied by b7_19
    Set r1 to r1 plus a5 multiplied by b6_19
    Set r1 to r1 plus a6 multiplied by b5_19
    Set r1 to r1 plus a7 multiplied by b4_19
    Set r1 to r1 plus a8 multiplied by b3_19
    Set r1 to r1 plus a9 multiplied by b2_19

    Note: r2 = a0*b2 + 2*a1*b1 + a2*b0 + 38*(a3*b9 + a5*b7 + a7*b5 + a9*b3) + 19*(a4*b8 + a6*b6 + a8*b4)
    Let r2 be a0 multiplied by b2
    Set r2 to r2 plus a1_2 multiplied by b1
    Set r2 to r2 plus a2 multiplied by b0
    Set r2 to r2 plus a3_2 multiplied by b9_19
    Set r2 to r2 plus a4 multiplied by b8_19
    Set r2 to r2 plus a5_2 multiplied by b7_19
    Set r2 to r2 plus a6 multiplied by b6_19
    Set r2 to r2 plus a7_2 multiplied by b5_19
    Set r2 to r2 plus a8 multiplied by b4_19
    Set r2 to r2 plus a9_2 multiplied by b3_19

    Note: r3 = a0*b3 + a1*b2 + a2*b1 + a3*b0 + 19*(a4*b9 + a5*b8 + a6*b7 + a7*b6 + a8*b5 + a9*b4)
    Let r3 be a0 multiplied by b3
    Set r3 to r3 plus a1 multiplied by b2
    Set r3 to r3 plus a2 multiplied by b1
    Set r3 to r3 plus a3 multiplied by b0
    Set r3 to r3 plus a4 multiplied by b9_19
    Set r3 to r3 plus a5 multiplied by b8_19
    Set r3 to r3 plus a6 multiplied by b7_19
    Set r3 to r3 plus a7 multiplied by b6_19
    Set r3 to r3 plus a8 multiplied by b5_19
    Set r3 to r3 plus a9 multiplied by b4_19

    Note: r4 = a0*b4 + 2*a1*b3 + a2*b2 + 2*a3*b1 + a4*b0 + 38*(a5*b9 + a7*b7 + a9*b5) + 19*(a6*b8 + a8*b6)
    Let r4 be a0 multiplied by b4
    Set r4 to r4 plus a1_2 multiplied by b3
    Set r4 to r4 plus a2 multiplied by b2
    Set r4 to r4 plus a3_2 multiplied by b1
    Set r4 to r4 plus a4 multiplied by b0
    Set r4 to r4 plus a5_2 multiplied by b9_19
    Set r4 to r4 plus a6 multiplied by b8_19
    Set r4 to r4 plus a7_2 multiplied by b7_19
    Set r4 to r4 plus a8 multiplied by b6_19
    Set r4 to r4 plus a9_2 multiplied by b5_19

    Note: r5 = a0*b5 + a1*b4 + a2*b3 + a3*b2 + a4*b1 + a5*b0 + 19*(a6*b9 + a7*b8 + a8*b7 + a9*b6)
    Let r5 be a0 multiplied by b5
    Set r5 to r5 plus a1 multiplied by b4
    Set r5 to r5 plus a2 multiplied by b3
    Set r5 to r5 plus a3 multiplied by b2
    Set r5 to r5 plus a4 multiplied by b1
    Set r5 to r5 plus a5 multiplied by b0
    Set r5 to r5 plus a6 multiplied by b9_19
    Set r5 to r5 plus a7 multiplied by b8_19
    Set r5 to r5 plus a8 multiplied by b7_19
    Set r5 to r5 plus a9 multiplied by b6_19

    Note: r6 = a0*b6 + 2*a1*b5 + a2*b4 + 2*a3*b3 + a4*b2 + 2*a5*b1 + a6*b0 + 38*(a7*b9 + a9*b7) + 19*(a8*b8)
    Let r6 be a0 multiplied by b6
    Set r6 to r6 plus a1_2 multiplied by b5
    Set r6 to r6 plus a2 multiplied by b4
    Set r6 to r6 plus a3_2 multiplied by b3
    Set r6 to r6 plus a4 multiplied by b2
    Set r6 to r6 plus a5_2 multiplied by b1
    Set r6 to r6 plus a6 multiplied by b0
    Set r6 to r6 plus a7_2 multiplied by b9_19
    Set r6 to r6 plus a8 multiplied by b8_19
    Set r6 to r6 plus a9_2 multiplied by b7_19

    Note: r7 = a0*b7 + a1*b6 + a2*b5 + a3*b4 + a4*b3 + a5*b2 + a6*b1 + a7*b0 + 19*(a8*b9 + a9*b8)
    Let r7 be a0 multiplied by b7
    Set r7 to r7 plus a1 multiplied by b6
    Set r7 to r7 plus a2 multiplied by b5
    Set r7 to r7 plus a3 multiplied by b4
    Set r7 to r7 plus a4 multiplied by b3
    Set r7 to r7 plus a5 multiplied by b2
    Set r7 to r7 plus a6 multiplied by b1
    Set r7 to r7 plus a7 multiplied by b0
    Set r7 to r7 plus a8 multiplied by b9_19
    Set r7 to r7 plus a9 multiplied by b8_19

    Note: r8 = a0*b8 + 2*a1*b7 + a2*b6 + 2*a3*b5 + a4*b4 + 2*a5*b3 + a6*b2 + 2*a7*b1 + a8*b0 + 38*a9*b9
    Let r8 be a0 multiplied by b8
    Set r8 to r8 plus a1_2 multiplied by b7
    Set r8 to r8 plus a2 multiplied by b6
    Set r8 to r8 plus a3_2 multiplied by b5
    Set r8 to r8 plus a4 multiplied by b4
    Set r8 to r8 plus a5_2 multiplied by b3
    Set r8 to r8 plus a6 multiplied by b2
    Set r8 to r8 plus a7_2 multiplied by b1
    Set r8 to r8 plus a8 multiplied by b0
    Set r8 to r8 plus a9_2 multiplied by b9_19

    Note: r9 = a0*b9 + a1*b8 + a2*b7 + a3*b6 + a4*b5 + a5*b4 + a6*b3 + a7*b2 + a8*b1 + a9*b0
    Let r9 be a0 multiplied by b9
    Set r9 to r9 plus a1 multiplied by b8
    Set r9 to r9 plus a2 multiplied by b7
    Set r9 to r9 plus a3 multiplied by b6
    Set r9 to r9 plus a4 multiplied by b5
    Set r9 to r9 plus a5 multiplied by b4
    Set r9 to r9 plus a6 multiplied by b3
    Set r9 to r9 plus a7 multiplied by b2
    Set r9 to r9 plus a8 multiplied by b1
    Set r9 to r9 plus a9 multiplied by b0

    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 0, r0)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 8, r1)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 16, r2)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 24, r3)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 32, r4)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 40, r5)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 48, r6)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 56, r7)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 64, r8)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 72, r9)

    proc fe25519_carry with dest
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe25519_sqr" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Squaring of a 10-limb radix-2^25.5 field element. Implemented as
    fe25519_mul(dest, a, a). A specialized squaring schedule can save
    ~30% over the general multiplication by collapsing symmetric cross
    products (a_i*a_j + a_j*a_i = 2*a_i*a_j), but the speedup requires
    the 26/25 parity bookkeeping to be handled correctly. The simpler
    derivation below uses the same well-tested multiplication kernel
    and pays one extra multiplication group per limb (a factor of ~2
    on the squaring kernel itself, but identical correctness).

    For Ed25519 / X25519, the 255-squaring inversion chain dominates;
    we accept the constant factor cost in exchange for sharing a
    single audited reduction kernel between mul and sqr.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegates to fe25519_mul with b = a. Preserves a's storage because
    fe25519_mul loads all source limbs into registers before any write
    to dest, so dest=a aliasing is safe (callers always pass an
    independent dest buffer here; if aliasing is ever needed, the
    fe25519_mul source-load-before-store property holds).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost profile as fe25519_mul (100 multiplications + 100
    additions + 10 carries). For workloads dominated by squaring
    (Fermat inversion's 255 squarings), this is the bottleneck, but
    the constant-factor benefit of a specialized squaring kernel is
    deferred to keep one reduction kernel under audit.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time, inherited from fe25519_mul.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc fe25519_mul with dest, a, a
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5: Constant-time conditional swap and equality
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe25519_cswap" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, swap_bit as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Conditionally swaps two field elements based on a single bit, without
    branching. When swap_bit = 1, the contents of a and b are exchanged;
    when swap_bit = 0, both are unchanged. This is the core primitive that
    makes the Montgomery ladder constant-time: each ladder step CSWAPs the
    two accumulator points based on the current scalar bit, ensuring the
    same memory accesses regardless of the bit's value.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    For each limb i:
      mask = -swap_bit              (all-ones if swap_bit=1, all-zero if 0)
      t = mask AND (a[i] XOR b[i])
      a[i] = a[i] XOR t
      b[i] = b[i] XOR t
    When swap_bit=0, mask=0 so t=0 and both limbs are unchanged. When
    swap_bit=1, mask=-1 so t=a[i] XOR b[i], and XOR-ing both sides
    completes the swap.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    10 iterations, each 4 arithmetic ops and 2 stores. ~40ns on modern
    cores. The compiler is free to lower the loop as a fixed unrolled
    sequence.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: identical instruction sequence regardless of swap_bit.
    The mask construction has no branches.
    Precondition: swap_bit must be 0 or 1; callers should normalize via
    secure_memory.normalize_to_bool if uncertain.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mask be 0 minus swap_bit
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 10:
        Let ai be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, i multiplied by 8)
        Let bi be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, i multiplied by 8)
        Let xored be ai bitwise_xor bi
        Let t be xored bitwise_and mask
        Let new_a be ai bitwise_xor t
        Let new_b be bi bitwise_xor t
        Memory.memory_set_qword(a, i multiplied by 8, new_a)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(b, i multiplied by 8, new_b)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe25519_select" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer, condition as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constant-time conditional move: dest := a when condition = 1,
    dest := b when condition = 0. Both source elements are read on
    every call to prevent cache-side-channel leakage of the condition.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. The selection is performed via bitwise mask, with no
    branches and identical memory access pattern in both cases.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mask be 0 minus condition
    Let not_mask be mask bitwise_xor 0 minus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 10:
        Let ai be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, i multiplied by 8)
        Let bi be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, i multiplied by 8)
        Let from_a be ai bitwise_and mask
        Let from_b be bi bitwise_and not_mask
        Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, i multiplied by 8, from_a bitwise_or from_b)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6: Packing (field element -> 32 bytes) and unpacking
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe25519_unpack" takes fe as Integer, bytes32 as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decodes a 32-byte little-endian buffer into a 10-limb field element
    representation. The top bit of byte 31 is masked out (Ed25519's
    encoded points carry the sign of x in that bit; for X25519's u
    coordinate it must be cleared anyway per RFC 7748).

    Each 26-bit / 25-bit limb is extracted by combining bytes with the
    appropriate shift offset.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads bytes32[0..31] (with byte 31's top bit cleared), then computes
    each limb via byte-shift-add. Stores 10 limbs in fe.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: 32 byte reads, 32 byte combines, no branches.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let b0 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 0)
    Let b1 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 1)
    Let b2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 2)
    Let b3 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 3)
    Let b4 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 4)
    Let b5 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 5)
    Let b6 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 6)
    Let b7 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 7)
    Let b8 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 8)
    Let b9 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 9)
    Let b10 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 10)
    Let b11 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 11)
    Let b12 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 12)
    Let b13 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 13)
    Let b14 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 14)
    Let b15 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 15)
    Let b16 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 16)
    Let b17 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 17)
    Let b18 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 18)
    Let b19 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 19)
    Let b20 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 20)
    Let b21 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 21)
    Let b22 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 22)
    Let b23 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 23)
    Let b24 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 24)
    Let b25 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 25)
    Let b26 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 26)
    Let b27 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 27)
    Let b28 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 28)
    Let b29 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 29)
    Let b30 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 30)
    Let b31_raw be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes32, 31)
    Let b31 be b31_raw bitwise_and 127

    Note: limb 0 = bits   0..25   = b0 | b1<<8 | b2<<16 | (b3 & 0x03)<<24
    Let l0 be b0
    Set l0 to l0 plus b1 multiplied by 256
    Set l0 to l0 plus b2 multiplied by 65536
    Set l0 to l0 plus (b3 bitwise_and 3) multiplied by 16777216

    Note: limb 1 = bits  26..50   = (b3>>2) | b4<<6 | b5<<14 | (b6 & 0x07)<<22
    Let l1 be b3 shifted right by 2
    Set l1 to l1 plus b4 multiplied by 64
    Set l1 to l1 plus b5 multiplied by 16384
    Set l1 to l1 plus (b6 bitwise_and 7) multiplied by 4194304

    Note: limb 2 = bits  51..76   = (b6>>3) | b7<<5 | b8<<13 | (b9 & 0x1F)<<21
    Let l2 be b6 shifted right by 3
    Set l2 to l2 plus b7 multiplied by 32
    Set l2 to l2 plus b8 multiplied by 8192
    Set l2 to l2 plus (b9 bitwise_and 31) multiplied by 2097152

    Note: limb 3 = bits  77..101  = (b9>>5) | b10<<3 | b11<<11 | (b12 & 0x3F)<<19
    Let l3 be b9 shifted right by 5
    Set l3 to l3 plus b10 multiplied by 8
    Set l3 to l3 plus b11 multiplied by 2048
    Set l3 to l3 plus (b12 bitwise_and 63) multiplied by 524288

    Note: limb 4 = bits 102..127  = (b12>>6) | b13<<2 | b14<<10 | b15<<18
    Let l4 be b12 shifted right by 6
    Set l4 to l4 plus b13 multiplied by 4
    Set l4 to l4 plus b14 multiplied by 1024
    Set l4 to l4 plus b15 multiplied by 262144

    Note: limb 5 = bits 128..152  = b16 | b17<<8 | b18<<16 | (b19 & 0x01)<<24
    Let l5 be b16
    Set l5 to l5 plus b17 multiplied by 256
    Set l5 to l5 plus b18 multiplied by 65536
    Set l5 to l5 plus (b19 bitwise_and 1) multiplied by 16777216

    Note: limb 6 = bits 153..178  = (b19>>1) | b20<<7 | b21<<15 | (b22 & 0x07)<<23
    Let l6 be b19 shifted right by 1
    Set l6 to l6 plus b20 multiplied by 128
    Set l6 to l6 plus b21 multiplied by 32768
    Set l6 to l6 plus (b22 bitwise_and 7) multiplied by 8388608

    Note: limb 7 = bits 179..203  = (b22>>3) | b23<<5 | b24<<13 | (b25 & 0x1F)<<21
    Let l7 be b22 shifted right by 3
    Set l7 to l7 plus b23 multiplied by 32
    Set l7 to l7 plus b24 multiplied by 8192
    Set l7 to l7 plus (b25 bitwise_and 31) multiplied by 2097152

    Note: limb 8 = bits 204..229  = (b25>>5) | b26<<3 | b27<<11 | (b28 & 0x3F)<<19
    Let l8 be b25 shifted right by 5
    Set l8 to l8 plus b26 multiplied by 8
    Set l8 to l8 plus b27 multiplied by 2048
    Set l8 to l8 plus (b28 bitwise_and 63) multiplied by 524288

    Note: limb 9 = bits 230..254  = (b28>>6) | b29<<2 | b30<<10 | b31<<18
    Let l9 be b28 shifted right by 6
    Set l9 to l9 plus b29 multiplied by 4
    Set l9 to l9 plus b30 multiplied by 1024
    Set l9 to l9 plus b31 multiplied by 262144

    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 0, l0)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 8, l1)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 16, l2)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 24, l3)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 32, l4)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 40, l5)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 48, l6)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 56, l7)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 64, l8)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 72, l9)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe25519_freeze" takes fe as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reduces a field element to its unique canonical representative in
    [0, p). This is required before packing back to bytes because the
    raw limbs may represent a value >= p (specifically, the result of
    earlier arithmetic may be in [0, 2p) due to the lazy reduction).

    The canonical reduction subtracts p from fe and selects the result
    based on whether the subtraction underflowed: if fe < p, the
    original is correct; if fe >= p, the reduced value is correct.

    Two carry passes are performed before the comparison to ensure each
    limb is in its target range. Then a comparison-and-subtract pattern
    handles the wrap from values >= p.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Standard ref10 fe_tobytes pre-step. The pattern:
      1. Carry-propagate (two passes).
      2. Add 19 to h[0] and carry through; if h[9] overflowed, the
         result was >= p and we keep the +19 addition.
      3. Otherwise subtract 19 back from h[0] and clear the carry.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: the comparison-and-subtract is implemented as
    arithmetic with conditional masks, not branches.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Two carry passes to bring all limbs into their canonical
    Note: range [0, 2^bitsize).
    proc fe25519_carry with fe
    proc fe25519_carry with fe

    Note: Compute h + 19. If h + 19 has its high (limb 9) bit set above
    Note: 2^24, then h was already >= 2^255 - 19, so the true value is
    Note: h - (p - 19) = h - p + 19. We mask all limbs by either keeping
    Note: them or subtracting p.
    Note: Equivalent classical approach: Try h - p and use h - p if it
    Note: didn't underflow. Implemented via carry-out detection.

    Let h0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 0)
    Let h1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 8)
    Let h2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 16)
    Let h3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 24)
    Let h4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 32)
    Let h5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 40)
    Let h6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 48)
    Let h7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 56)
    Let h8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 64)
    Let h9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 72)

    Note: First conditional subtraction of p. q = (h + 19) >> 255 indicates
    Note: whether h >= p - 19; we then subtract p by adjusting h[0] by -19
    Note: and clearing the top bit of h[9].
    Let q0 be h0 plus 19
    Let q be q0 shifted right by 26
    Set q to (h1 plus q) shifted right by 25
    Set q to (h2 plus q) shifted right by 26
    Set q to (h3 plus q) shifted right by 25
    Set q to (h4 plus q) shifted right by 26
    Set q to (h5 plus q) shifted right by 25
    Set q to (h6 plus q) shifted right by 26
    Set q to (h7 plus q) shifted right by 25
    Set q to (h8 plus q) shifted right by 26
    Set q to (h9 plus q) shifted right by 25

    Note: q is now 0 if h < p, 1 if h >= p (when h >= p we want to subtract p).
    Set h0 to h0 plus 19 multiplied by q

    Let mask26 be 67108863
    Let mask25 be 33554431

    Note: Now propagate carries with bitmask of each limb to its range.
    Let h1n be h1 plus (h0 shifted right by 26)
    Let h0n be h0 bitwise_and mask26
    Let h2n be h2 plus (h1n shifted right by 25)
    Let h1m be h1n bitwise_and mask25
    Let h3n be h3 plus (h2n shifted right by 26)
    Let h2m be h2n bitwise_and mask26
    Let h4n be h4 plus (h3n shifted right by 25)
    Let h3m be h3n bitwise_and mask25
    Let h5n be h5 plus (h4n shifted right by 26)
    Let h4m be h4n bitwise_and mask26
    Let h6n be h6 plus (h5n shifted right by 25)
    Let h5m be h5n bitwise_and mask25
    Let h7n be h7 plus (h6n shifted right by 26)
    Let h6m be h6n bitwise_and mask26
    Let h8n be h8 plus (h7n shifted right by 25)
    Let h7m be h7n bitwise_and mask25
    Let h9n be h9 plus (h8n shifted right by 26)
    Let h8m be h8n bitwise_and mask26
    Let h9m be h9n bitwise_and mask25

    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 0, h0n)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 8, h1m)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 16, h2m)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 24, h3m)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 32, h4m)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 40, h5m)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 48, h6m)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 56, h7m)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 64, h8m)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 72, h9m)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe25519_pack" takes fe as Integer, bytes32 as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Packs a field element to its 32-byte little-endian canonical form.
    Calls fe25519_freeze first to ensure the limbs represent the unique
    value in [0, p), then writes each byte by combining bits from the
    two limbs that span its position.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: writes 32 bytes regardless of value. fe25519_freeze
    itself is constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc fe25519_freeze with fe

    Let h0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 0)
    Let h1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 8)
    Let h2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 16)
    Let h3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 24)
    Let h4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 32)
    Let h5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 40)
    Let h6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 48)
    Let h7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 56)
    Let h8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 64)
    Let h9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 72)

    Note: byte 0  = limb0 bits  0..7
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 0, h0 bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 1  = limb0 bits  8..15
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 1, (h0 shifted right by 8) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 2  = limb0 bits 16..23
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 2, (h0 shifted right by 16) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 3  = limb0 bits 24..25 | limb1 bits 0..5
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 3, ((h0 shifted right by 24) bitwise_or (h1 multiplied by 4)) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 4  = limb1 bits  6..13
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 4, (h1 shifted right by 6) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 5  = limb1 bits 14..21
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 5, (h1 shifted right by 14) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 6  = limb1 bits 22..24 | limb2 bits 0..4
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 6, ((h1 shifted right by 22) bitwise_or (h2 multiplied by 8)) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 7  = limb2 bits  5..12
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 7, (h2 shifted right by 5) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 8  = limb2 bits 13..20
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 8, (h2 shifted right by 13) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 9  = limb2 bits 21..25 | limb3 bits 0..2
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 9, ((h2 shifted right by 21) bitwise_or (h3 multiplied by 32)) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 10 = limb3 bits  3..10
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 10, (h3 shifted right by 3) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 11 = limb3 bits 11..18
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 11, (h3 shifted right by 11) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 12 = limb3 bits 19..24 | limb4 bits 0..1
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 12, ((h3 shifted right by 19) bitwise_or (h4 multiplied by 64)) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 13 = limb4 bits  2..9
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 13, (h4 shifted right by 2) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 14 = limb4 bits 10..17
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 14, (h4 shifted right by 10) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 15 = limb4 bits 18..25
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 15, (h4 shifted right by 18) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 16 = limb5 bits  0..7
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 16, h5 bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 17 = limb5 bits  8..15
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 17, (h5 shifted right by 8) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 18 = limb5 bits 16..23
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 18, (h5 shifted right by 16) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 19 = limb5 bit 24 | limb6 bits 0..6
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 19, ((h5 shifted right by 24) bitwise_or (h6 multiplied by 2)) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 20 = limb6 bits  7..14
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 20, (h6 shifted right by 7) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 21 = limb6 bits 15..22
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 21, (h6 shifted right by 15) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 22 = limb6 bits 23..25 | limb7 bits 0..4
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 22, ((h6 shifted right by 23) bitwise_or (h7 multiplied by 8)) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 23 = limb7 bits  5..12
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 23, (h7 shifted right by 5) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 24 = limb7 bits 13..20
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 24, (h7 shifted right by 13) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 25 = limb7 bits 21..24 | limb8 bits 0..2
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 25, ((h7 shifted right by 21) bitwise_or (h8 multiplied by 32)) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 26 = limb8 bits  3..10
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 26, (h8 shifted right by 3) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 27 = limb8 bits 11..18
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 27, (h8 shifted right by 11) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 28 = limb8 bits 19..25 | limb9 bit 0
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 28, ((h8 shifted right by 19) bitwise_or (h9 multiplied by 64)) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 29 = limb9 bits  1..8
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 29, (h9 shifted right by 1) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 30 = limb9 bits  9..16
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 30, (h9 shifted right by 9) bitwise_and 255)
    Note: byte 31 = limb9 bits 17..24 (top bit is zero in canonical form)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes32, 31, (h9 shifted right by 17) bitwise_and 127)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7: Equality and zero tests
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe25519_is_zero" takes fe as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constant-time zero test. Returns 1 if fe == 0 (mod p), else 0.
    Packs the freeze-reduced element to bytes and ORs them together;
    the result is 0 iff every byte was 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: writes 32 bytes (via pack), reads them all
    unconditionally, returns a bit derived purely from the OR.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let bytes_buffer be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 0)
    Note: We need a temporary 32-byte buffer; using an inline scratch on
    Note: a copy of the field element. Caller must have spare arena space.
    Note: Instead we test via direct limb inspection after freeze.

    proc fe25519_freeze with fe

    Let h0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 0)
    Let h1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 8)
    Let h2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 16)
    Let h3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 24)
    Let h4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 32)
    Let h5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 40)
    Let h6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 48)
    Let h7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 56)
    Let h8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 64)
    Let h9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 72)

    Let or_acc be h0
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or h1
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or h2
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or h3
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or h4
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or h5
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or h6
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or h7
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or h8
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or h9

    Note: Map nonzero to 1, zero to 0. Use (x | -x) >> 63 then invert.
    Let neg_or be 0 minus or_acc
    Let or_or_neg be or_acc bitwise_or neg_or
    Let nonzero_bit be (or_or_neg shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Return 1 minus nonzero_bit
End Process

Process called "fe25519_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constant-time equality test. Subtracts b from a and checks the
    result for zero. The caller is responsible for the temporary buffer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: uses fe25519_sub + fe25519_is_zero, both of which
    are constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let diff_buffer be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 0)
    Note: Direct comparison without an extra buffer: freeze both copies
    Note: in-place is unsafe since we'd mutate caller storage. So we
    Note: re-derive equality from packed bytes via per-limb XOR after
    Note: freezing. To avoid mutating caller state, we operate on the
    Note: limb differences in registers.

    Let a0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 0)
    Let a1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 8)
    Let a2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 16)
    Let a3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 24)
    Let a4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 32)
    Let a5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 40)
    Let a6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 48)
    Let a7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 56)
    Let a8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 64)
    Let a9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 72)

    Let b0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 0)
    Let b1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 8)
    Let b2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 16)
    Let b3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 24)
    Let b4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 32)
    Let b5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 40)
    Let b6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 48)
    Let b7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 56)
    Let b8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 64)
    Let b9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 72)

    Let or_acc be a0 bitwise_xor b0
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or (a1 bitwise_xor b1)
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or (a2 bitwise_xor b2)
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or (a3 bitwise_xor b3)
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or (a4 bitwise_xor b4)
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or (a5 bitwise_xor b5)
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or (a6 bitwise_xor b6)
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or (a7 bitwise_xor b7)
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or (a8 bitwise_xor b8)
    Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or (a9 bitwise_xor b9)

    Note: NOTE: This bit-pattern equality test requires both a and b to be
    Note: in canonical form (post-freeze). Callers must freeze before
    Note: comparing. For modular equality, the caller should fe25519_sub
    Note: and call fe25519_is_zero (which freezes internally).

    Let neg_or be 0 minus or_acc
    Let or_or_neg be or_acc bitwise_or neg_or
    Let nonzero_bit be (or_or_neg shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Return 1 minus nonzero_bit
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 8: Field inversion (a^-1 mod p via Fermat: a^(p-2))
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe25519_inv" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the multiplicative inverse of a in F_p via Fermat's little
    theorem: a^(p-2) = a^-1 (mod p), where p = 2^255 - 19, so
    p - 2 = 2^255 - 21.

    Uses an addition chain that minimizes the number of squarings and
    multiplications. The chain (ref10 fe_invert): 255 squarings + 11
    multiplications, total 266 field operations.

    Addition chain (writing S=square, M=multiply by a):
      z2     = a^2     (S)
      z9     = z2^4 * a (S S M)
      z11    = z9 * z2  (M)
      z22    = z11^2    (S)
      z2_5_0 = z9 * z22  (M)           = a^(2^5 - 1)
      z2_10_0 = z2_5_0^32 * z2_5_0     = a^(2^10 - 1)
      z2_20_0 = z2_10_0^1024 * z2_10_0 = a^(2^20 - 1)
      z2_40_0 = z2_20_0^(2^20) * z2_20_0 = a^(2^40 - 1)
      z2_50_0 = z2_40_0^(2^10) * z2_10_0 = a^(2^50 - 1)
      z2_100_0= z2_50_0^(2^50) * z2_50_0 = a^(2^100 - 1)
      z2_200_0= z2_100_0^(2^100)*z2_100_0= a^(2^200 - 1)
      z2_250_0= z2_200_0^(2^50)*z2_50_0  = a^(2^250 - 1)
      result  = z2_250_0^32 * z11        = a^(2^255 - 21) = a^(p-2)
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    All intermediate field elements are allocated in the arena. The
    inversion runs in constant time because every multiplication and
    squaring kernel is constant-time and the chain has no data-dependent
    branches.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    255 squarings + 11 multiplications. With each squaring at ~30 IMULs
    and each multiplication at ~100 IMULs, the total cost is roughly
    8800 IMULs, dominated by the squaring chain. The Itoh-Tsujii method
    via tower extensions would not help here because GF(2^255 - 19) is a
    prime field; Fermat is optimal for this prime size.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time end to end: the chain length is fixed at compile time
    and no operation branches on operand values.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let t0 be proc fe25519_alloc with arena
    Let t1 be proc fe25519_alloc with arena
    Let t2 be proc fe25519_alloc with arena
    Let t3 be proc fe25519_alloc with arena
    If t0 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If t1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If t2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If t3 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: z2 = a^2
    proc fe25519_sqr with t0, a
    Note: z2 -> z4
    proc fe25519_sqr with t1, t0
    Note: z4 -> z8
    proc fe25519_sqr with t1, t1
    Note: z9 = z8 * a
    proc fe25519_mul with t1, t1, a
    Note: z11 = z9 * z2
    proc fe25519_mul with t0, t1, t0
    Note: z22 = z11^2
    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t0
    Note: z2_5_0 = z22 * z9
    proc fe25519_mul with t1, t2, t1

    Note: z2_10_0 = z2_5_0^32 * z2_5_0
    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t1
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than 5:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t1, t2, t1

    Note: z2_20_0 = z2_10_0^(2^10) * z2_10_0
    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t1
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 10:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t2, t2, t1

    Note: z2_40_0 = z2_20_0^(2^20) * z2_20_0
    proc fe25519_sqr with t3, t2
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 20:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t3, t3
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t2, t3, t2

    Note: z2_50_0 = z2_40_0^(2^10) * z2_10_0
    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 10:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t1, t2, t1

    Note: z2_100_0 = z2_50_0^(2^50) * z2_50_0
    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t1
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 50:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t2, t2, t1

    Note: z2_200_0 = z2_100_0^(2^100) * z2_100_0
    proc fe25519_sqr with t3, t2
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 100:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t3, t3
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t2, t3, t2

    Note: z2_250_0 = z2_200_0^(2^50) * z2_50_0
    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 50:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t1, t2, t1

    Note: result = z2_250_0^32 * z11
    proc fe25519_sqr with t1, t1
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 5:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t1, t1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with dest, t1, t0

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 9: Power by (p-5)/8 for sqrt and decompression (Ed25519)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe25519_pow_p_minus_5_div_8" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes a^((p-5)/8). Used in Ed25519 point decompression and
    square-root extraction. (p-5)/8 = 2^252 - 3.

    The chain reuses the structure of fe25519_inv but stops earlier
    and applies a different final step.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reuses the z2_250_0 sub-chain from fe25519_inv (a^(2^250 - 1)),
    then squares twice and multiplies by a:
      z2_252_3 = z2_250_0^4 * a = a^(2^252 - 4 + 1) = a^(2^252 - 3)
    Total: 252 squarings + ~10 multiplications.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    ~99% of the cost of fe25519_inv.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time, identical reasoning to fe25519_inv.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let t0 be proc fe25519_alloc with arena
    Let t1 be proc fe25519_alloc with arena
    Let t2 be proc fe25519_alloc with arena
    Let t3 be proc fe25519_alloc with arena
    If t0 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If t1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If t2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If t3 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc fe25519_sqr with t0, a
    proc fe25519_sqr with t1, t0
    proc fe25519_sqr with t1, t1
    proc fe25519_mul with t1, t1, a
    proc fe25519_mul with t0, t1, t0
    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t0
    proc fe25519_mul with t1, t2, t1

    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t1
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than 5:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t1, t2, t1

    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t1
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 10:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t2, t2, t1

    proc fe25519_sqr with t3, t2
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 20:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t3, t3
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t2, t3, t2

    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 10:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t1, t2, t1

    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t1
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 50:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t2, t2, t1

    proc fe25519_sqr with t3, t2
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 100:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t3, t3
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t2, t3, t2

    proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
    Set i to 1
    While i is less than 50:
        proc fe25519_sqr with t2, t2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc fe25519_mul with t1, t2, t1

    Note: Final step: square twice then multiply by a -> a^(2^252 - 3)
    proc fe25519_sqr with t1, t1
    proc fe25519_sqr with t1, t1
    proc fe25519_mul with dest, t1, a

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 10: Sign / negative test
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe25519_is_negative" takes fe as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the least significant bit of the canonical representative,
    used to encode the sign of x in Ed25519's point compression
    (RFC 8032 5.1.2). Requires the input to be normalized via
    fe25519_freeze before reading the low bit. This routine
    auto-freezes for safety.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: writes 80 bytes (freeze) + one byte read + one mask.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc fe25519_freeze with fe
    Let h0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 0)
    Return h0 bitwise_and 1
End Process
